title.narrative: EARLY CHILDHOOD DEVELOPMENT

description.narrative: By 2025, national and local health and other service providers and stakeholders have improved understanding, standards and skills to deliver culturally and gender sensitive, high quality integrated early childhood development and early childhood intervention services and programmes for all children from conception to 6 years of age benefiting their development and inclusion and empowering and capacitating parents to adopt positive nurturing care practice, which contributes to Health And Development In Early Childhood And Adolescence, Health And Development In Early Childhood And Adolescence (Covid), Nutrition In Early Childhood, Nutrition Of Adolescents And Women, Strengthening Primary Health Care And High-Impact Health Interventions, Strengthening Primary Health Care And High-Impact Health Interventions (Covid). UNICEF aims to achieve this through Advocacy And Public Engagement, Community Engagement, Social And Behaviour Change, Developing And Leveraging Resources And Partnerships, Evaluations, Research And Data, Fostering Innovation And Use Of New Technologies, Operational Support To Programme Delivery, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building, Systems Strengthening To Leave No One Behind. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: Girls and boys from conception to age 6, especially the most marginalized and those living in humanitarian settings, and their parents/families will benefit from high-impact health, nutrition and other interventions that support nurturing care for early childhood development, enabling children to survive and thrive.

description.narrative: Relying on multisectoral ECD policies, UNICEF supported national and local efforts in advancing the Nurturing Care Framework through programming, coordination and financing. The modelling of cross-sectoral ECD and ECI services is bringing new knowledge to facilitate scale-up across the country. The network of ECD allies and stakeholders was expanded and the political commitment increased for family strengthening and inclusion of disadvantaged children. The contribution of spreading evidence-based messages on the importance of ECI and nurturing care for children during the pandemic, including focus on parental and child mental health and well-being, was highly acknowledged | Status:On-track | As-of Date:04/01/2022
